'''Konstantinos '''"'''Kosta'''"''' Barbarouses''' ({{langx|el|Κωνσταντίνος "Κώστας" Μπαρμπαρούσης}}, {{IPA|el|konstaˈndinos barbaruˈsis|pron}};<ref name=":0">https://www.instagram.com/reel/DPyDwrxiaCT/?igsh=dXQ0a2R3cjRkem1t</ref> born 19 February 1990) is a [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[winger (association football)|winger]] for [[A-League Men]] club [[Western Sydney Wanderers FC|Western Sydney Wanderers]] and the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].

As of March 2026, he has 377 appearances, the most of any active player in the A-League.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Player Statistics (Appearances) :: Appearances (All) : |url=https://www.ultimatealeague.com/statistics/player/?type=pa&season=all |access-date=2026-03-24 |website=Ultimate A-League |language=en}}</ref>

== Club career ==
Kosta was born in New Zealand and is of Greek descent. Before turning professional Barbarouses played for [[St. Patrick's College, Wellington|St. Patrick's College]] and for local clubs [[Wellington Olympic]] and [[Miramar Rangers]] in New Zealand's [[Central Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Kosta Barbarouses Olympic Team |url=https://olympic.org.nz/athletes/kosta-barbarouses |website=Olympics NZ |date=9 February 2016 |access-date=12 July 2019}}</ref>

===Wellington Phoenix===
[[File:CostaB.jpg|thumb|left|222px|Kosta Barbarouses with [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]] in 2009.]]

Barbarouses played 21 matches during his first stint with [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]] in three seasons and scored two goals. The Phoenix club officially signed Barbarouses as one of its foundation players on 4 May 2007. Seventeen years old and still at school, he started as the club's youngest player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infonews.co.nz/news.cfm?l=86&t=1&id=1350|title=Phoenix signs up schoolboy|publisher=Infonews.co.nz|date=4 May 2007}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He made his professional debut on 21 October 2007 against [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]], coming on as a substitute in the 86th minute. He played his first full professional game when he fronted against [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] on 19 January 2008.{{Citation needed|date=June 2026}}

Barbarouses scored his first professional goal on 18 January 2009 – an equaliser against [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]]. He scored his second A-League goal against [[Sydney FC]] on 1 November 2009 after coming off the bench to replace [[Leo Bertos]]. He scored the goal off a volley which bounced over [[Clint Bolton]]. Barbarouses played his first match starting in the first team line-up against [[Newcastle United Jets FC|Newcastle Jets]] on 4 November 2009, assisting [[Chris Greenacre]]'s goal with a back-heel pass.{{Citation needed|date=June 2026}}

===Brisbane Roar===
Barbarouses turned down a two-year contract extension with Wellington Phoenix in February 2010 for a three-year contract with A-League side [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/3318724/Barbarouses-dumps-Phoenix-joins-Brisbane-Roar|title=Barbarouses dumps Phoenix, joins Brisbane Roar|publisher=stuff.co.nz|date=11 February 2010}}</ref><ref name="TVNZ_3362095">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/football-news/phoenix-lose-young-star-brisbane-3362095 |title=Phoenix lose young star to Brisbane |date=12 February 2010 |agency=[[NZPA]] |work=[[Television New Zealand]] |access-date=13 October 2011}}</ref> Brisbane Roar play an attractive brand of football and Barbarouses wanted the opportunity to play more regular football.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/4300996|title=Barbarouses home and looking to roar again|date=2 November 2010}}</ref> In the 2009–10 season, which took the Phoenix into the finals, Barbarouses had had only three starts, and ten appearances off the bench.{{Citation needed|date=June 2026}}

Barbarouses made his debut for the Roar in Round 1 of the 2010–11 season, starting against [[Gold Coast United FC|Gold Coast United]] in a 0–0 draw on 8 August 2010. Barbarouses continued to start for the Brisbane team and played against his old club [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]], on 27 August 2010 at [[Suncorp Stadium]]. In the 73rd minute, he received a through-ball from team-mate [[Matt McKay]] and slotted home his first [[A-League]] goal for the [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]]. Barbarouses was named in the 2010–11 A-League All-Star Team after 12 goals in 33 appearances.{{Citation needed|date=June 2026}}

===Alania Vladikavkaz===
On 18 July 2011, [[Fairfax New Zealand|Fairfax News NZ]] announced that Barbarouses had signed a three-year contract with Russian side [[FC Alania Vladikavkaz|Alania Vladikavkaz]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Worthington|first=Sam|title=All Whites Barbarouses signs with Russian Club|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/5298555/All-Whites-Barbarouses-signs-with-Russian-club|work=Stuff|access-date=9 February 2012|date=18 July 2011}}</ref>
Brisbane Roar received $600,000 as a transfer fee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fc-alania.ru/press/news/alaniya_podpisala_kontrakt_s_novozelandskim_forvardom |title=Футбольный клуб – Алания |access-date=2011-07-15 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120729190922/http://www.fc-alania.ru/press/news/alaniya_podpisala_kontrakt_s_novozelandskim_forvardom |archive-date=29 July 2012}}</ref><ref>http://au.fourfourtwo.com/News/209360,kosta-pens-russian-deal.aspx {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717005750/http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/209360,kosta-pens-russian-deal.aspx |date=17 July 2011 }} Kosta Pens Russian Deal</ref> Barbarouses made his debut for Vladikavkaz on 9 August 2011, in a [[Football Championship of the National League|First Division]] league match against [[FC Torpedo Vladimir|Torpedo Vladimir]]. He played the full 90 minutes and scored the sole goal of the match, allowing Alania to win 1–0.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ormond|first=Aidan|title=Kiwi Kosta's Dream Debut|url=http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/211510,kiwi-kostas-dream-debut.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110816005634/http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/211510,kiwi-kostas-dream-debut.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 August 2011|work=FourFourTwo|access-date=10 August 2011|date=10 August 2011}}</ref>

====Loan to Panathinaikos====
On 27 June 2012, Barbarouses signed a one-year loan contract with Greek giants [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10815794|title=Soccer: Barbarouses set for Panathinaikos|date=27 June 2012|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.in.gr/football/superleague/article/?aid=1231202438|title=Η ανακοίνωση για Μπαρμπαρούση και η πρώτη επαφή με Κατσουράνη (Announcement for Barbarouses and first touches for Katsouranis)|date=27 June 2012|publisher=[[In.gr]]|language=el|location=Athens}}</ref> with option to buy him in the next summer. Barbarouses only played 11 games and scored no goals during his one-year loan spell in his ancestral country. His stand out moment was when he played against Greatest Rivals Olympiacos in a league match in Piraeus in a 1–1 draw.{{Citation needed|date=June 2026}}

===Melbourne Victory===
On 7 August 2013, Kosta signed a three-year deal at [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]] under [[Ange Postecoglou]] for the second time. The first time was at rival team [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]], following a successful career start at home town team [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.melbournevictory.com.au/article/barbarouses-joins-melbourne-victory/nmn5dq5g8m5210thm71vt6whh|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309043449/http://www.melbournevictory.com.au/article/barbarouses-joins-melbourne-victory/nmn5dq5g8m5210thm71vt6whh|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 March 2016|title=Barbarouses joins Melbourne Victory|publisher=[[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]]|date=7 August 2013}}</ref>

Kosta debuted for Melbourne Victory in round 2 of the 2013–14 season in the 2–2 away draw with Adelaide United.<ref>{{cite web |title=Round two squad locked in – Melbourne Victory |url=https://melbournevictory.com.au/news/round-two-squad-locked |website=[[Melbourne Victory FC]]|date=17 October 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Victory snatches dramatic 2–2 draw against Adelaide |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-10-18/victory-snatches-dramatic-2-2-draw-with-adelaide/5032924 |work=ABC News |date=18 October 2013 |language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Adelaide United vs. Melbourne Victory – 18 October 2013 – Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/10/18/australia/a-league/adelaide-united/melbourne-victory-fc/1475171/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref>

===Return to Wellington Phoenix===
On 8 March 2016, it was announced that Barbarouses would leave [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]] at the end of the season to rejoin his hometown club [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]] on a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a-league.com.au/article/a-league-transfer-news-wellington-phoenix-sign-melbourne-victory-star/101zx43ydg8161je0h0rfm19xr|title=Transfer news: Phoenix sign Victory star|publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]]|date=8 March 2016}}</ref> On 5 June 2017, Phoenix announced they would be releasing Barbarouses following his request to leave for non-footballing reasons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wellington Phoenix agree to release star attacker Kosta Barbarouses|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/93343545/wellington-phoenix-agree-to-release-star-kosta-barbarouses|access-date=5 June 2017|date=5 June 2017}}</ref>

===Return to Melbourne Victory===
Following his release from [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]], Barbarouses rejoined former club [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]] on a two-year deal in June 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kosta Barbarouses returns to Melbourne Victory after Phoenix release|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/93634382/kosta-barbarouses-returns-to-melbourne-victory-after-phoenix-release|access-date=13 June 2017|publisher=Stuff.co.nz|date=13 June 2017}}</ref> In June 2019 Melbourne Victory announced that his contract ended and he declined an extension.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/football/a-league/kosta-barbarouses-parts-ways-with-melbourne-victory/news-story/d8546b29d081c88edd2dc86fd936d623|title=Kosta Barbarouses parts ways with Melbourne Victory|work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]]|date=6 June 2019}}</ref>

===Sydney FC===
On 7 June 2019, Barbarouses signed on a multi-year contract deal with [[Sydney FC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.myfootball.com.au/news/big-blue-bargain-barbarouses-signs-sydney-fc|title=Barbarouses signs for Sydney FC|last=Windon|first=Jacob|date=7 June 2019|publisher=My Football}}</ref>

=== Third stint at Wellington Phoenix ===
Having missed the majority of the 2021–22 season at Sydney FC due to an ankle fracture, Barbarouses returned to his hometown club for a third stint, signing a two-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web |title=K. Barbarouses – Wellington Phoenix |url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/squads/7wy9lh4qgnim12456qttxn85?competition=52kxi893484fk75l1h7sndlp0&teams=6j4xzc2g1eeafo6v1f38d4x22&selected=MEN,%20https://wellingtonphoenix.com/squads/7wy9lh4qgnim12456qttxn85?competition=52kxi893484fk75l1h7sndlp0&teams=6j4xzc2g1eeafo6v1f38d4x22&selected=MEN |access-date=2024-01-17 |website=wellingtonphoenix.com}}</ref> On 20 January 2025, Barbarouses scored his 100th A-League Men goal in a 2–1 away win against [[Macarthur FC]] at [[Campbelltown Sports Stadium]], [[Sydney]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360551655/wellington-phoenix-v-macarthur-league-men-all-you-need-know|title=Wellington Phoenix produce stirring comeback after Kosta Barbarouses scores 100th A-League Men goal|date=20 January 2025|access-date=20 January 2025|newspaper=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|author=Rollo, Phillip}}</ref>

Barbarouses left Wellington once again at the end of the [[2024-25 A-League Men|2024–25 season]], after a three season stint at the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/barbarouses-farewells-the-phoenix/|title=Barbarouses farewells the Phoenix|date=27 May 2025|publisher=[[Wellington Phoenix FC]]}}</ref>

===Western Sydney Wanderers===
Barbarouses joined the [[Western Sydney Wanderers FC|Western Sydney Wanderers]] for the [[2025-26 A-League Men|2025–26 season]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wswanderersfc.com.au/news/barbarouses-joins-wanderers-for-2025-26-season/|title=Barbarouses joins Wanderers for 2025/26 season |date=18 June 2025|publisher=[[Western Sydney Wanderers FC]]}}</ref> his fifth A-League club and the bitter [[Sydney Derby (A-Leagues)|Sydney Derby]] rivals of his former club, Sydney FC.{{Citation needed|date=June 2026}}

== International career ==
[[File:New Zealand-Portugal (24) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Barbarouses playing for New Zealand at the [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup]]]]

===New Zealand U-17===

Barbarouses captained New Zealand at the [[2007 FIFA U-17 World Cup|2007 U-17 World Cup]] in Korea. He scored five goals, including a [[hat-trick]], during the team's qualifying campaign to ensure progression to the finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/u17worldcup/korea2007/news/newsid=122435.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110175646/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/u17worldcup/korea2007/news/newsid=122435.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 November 2012|title=PNew Zealand cruise to Korea|publisher=FIFA|date=26 March 2007|access-date=7 November 2010}}</ref>

===New Zealand U-20===

As a member of the national Under-20 side he played an integral part in the [[2008 OFC U-20 Championship]] qualification tournament for the [[2009 FIFA U-20 World Cup|2009 Under-20 World Cup]], scoring two goals in the three pool matches. New Zealand did not qualify for the final tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Junior-All-Whites-shocked-by-Tahiti/tabid/415/articleID/84658/cat/277/Default.aspx|title=Junior All Whites shocked by Tahiti|publisher=[[3news.co.nz|3 NEWS]]|date=17 December 2008|access-date=28 December 2008|archive-date=4 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004142045/http://www.3news.co.nz/Junior-All-Whites-shocked-by-Tahiti/tabid/415/articleID/84658/cat/277/Default.aspx|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Beijing 2008===

Barbarouses played for New Zealand at the [[2008 OFC Men's Olympic Football Tournament]]. Although he scored four goals in the five pool matches at this 2008 Beijing Olympics qualifying tournament, Barbarouses was not selected for the final squad to travel to the Games.{{Citation needed|date=June 2026}}

===2010 World Cup===

Barbarouses made his senior debut in a [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|2010 FIFA World Cup]] qualifier against [[Fiji national football team|Fiji]] on 19 November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/oceania/matches/round=250488/match=300036893/report.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215110218/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/oceania/matches/round=250488/match=300036893/report.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 February 2009|title=2008 OFC Nations Cup – Match Report: FIJ v NZL|publisher=FIFA|access-date=20 November 2008}}</ref>
He trained with the national team before its [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (inter-confederation play-offs)|World Cup qualifying play-off]] against [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]]. Barbarouses attended a 12-day [[All Whites]] training camp in Auckland in April–May 2010 as a member of a 15-man squad of Australasian-based players. He was one of two forwards on the squad.{{Citation needed|date=June 2026}}

Barbarouses had stated that he would like to make the New Zealand [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] squad.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/116952,costa-targets-world-cup-slot.aspx |title=Costa Targets World Cup Slot – Australia News – Australian FourFourTwo – the Ultimate Football Website |access-date=21 November 2009 |archive-date=20 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920020446/http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/116952,costa-targets-world-cup-slot.aspx |url-status=dead }}</ref> Although widely tipped to make the final 23-man squad travel to the 2010 FIFA World Cup, Barbarouses' name was missing when [[New Zealand Football|NZFA]] chairman [[Frank van Hattum]] read out the names at Auckland's Sky City on 10 May 2010. He was, however, named as one of seven non-travelling reserves.

===2011–current===
{{Update section|date=March 2019}}
A standout first season with then newly crowned A-League champions [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]] saw the 21-year-old striker included in the [[New Zealand national soccer team|New Zealand]] squad for a friendly against [[China national football team|China]] in [[Wuhan]] on 25 March 2011.{{Citation needed|date=June 2026}}

Barbarouses made the 23-man All Whites squad, where played against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] at altitude in [[Denver]] on 2 June and against [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]] in [[Adelaide]] on 5 June.{{Citation needed|date=June 2026}}

Barbarouses formed part of an 18-man All Whites squad that played [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] in an [[Friendly match|international friendly]] at [[Mt Smart Stadium]] in [[Auckland]], New Zealand, on 29 February 2012.{{Citation needed|date=June 2026}}

On 23 May 2012, Barbarouses scored his first goal for the All Whites in a friendly match against [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]]. His 64th-minute half-volley from close range levelled the scores and the match resulted in a 2–2 draw.<ref>
{{cite web|title=El Salvador, New Zealand draw 2–2 in exhibition
|url= http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/soccer/wires/05/23/2050.ap.soc.el.salvador.new.zealand.1st.ld.writethru.0268/index.html
|archive-url= https://archive.today/20120717143525/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/soccer/wires/05/23/2050.ap.soc.el.salvador.new.zealand.1st.ld.writethru.0268/index.html
|url-status= dead
|archive-date= 17 July 2012
|publisher=Sports Illustrated|access-date=24 May 2012}}
</ref>

He played for New Zealand at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ba/kosta-barbarouses-1.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418074606/https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ba/kosta-barbarouses-1.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-04-18|title=Kosta Barbarouses Bio, Stats, and Results|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref>

Barbarouses was also selected as a member of the All Whites squad for the June 2017 friendly vs Japan.{{Citation needed|date=June 2026}}

Barbarouses was a member of New Zealands Qualification campaign for the 2018 World Cup in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/matchstats?gameId=497671|title=New Zealand vs. Peru – Football Match Stats – November 10, 2017 – ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref> He played in both the home and away matches vs Peru in November 2017 as New Zealand ultimately were unsuccessful in their qualification bid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/matchstats?gameId=497671|title=New Zealand vs. Peru – Football Match Stats – November 10, 2017 – ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>

